It appears that you are getting an **uncaught** `NullPointerException` somewhere in this code:

    static Logger LOGGER;

    static {
        try (FileInputStream ins = new FileInputStream(&quot;src/main/resources/log.config&quot;)) {
            LogManager.getLogManager().readConfiguration(ins);
            LOGGER = Logger.getLogger(JavaFxRun.class.getName());
        } catch (Exception e) {
            LOGGER.log(Level.WARNING, &quot;Error &quot;, e);
        }
    }

It is a bit tricky to work out which exact line this is happening on (i.e. which line is line 16 of JavaFxRun.java) but think that the problem is this line:

         LOGGER.log(Level.WARNING, &quot;Error &quot;, e);

As far as I can tell, that is the *only* line that *could* throw an NPE.  Here&#39;s how it happens:

   1.  You attempt to open &quot;src/main/resources/log.config&quot;.
   2.  That throws a `FileNotFoundException` because (presumably) that file is not at the expected file system location *when application is run outside of your IDE*.
   3.  The FNFE is caught by your `catch (Exception e) {...}`
   4.  You attempt call a method via the `LOGGER` variables ... and NPE.  

The NPE happens because `LOGGER` didn&#39;t get initialized.  And that happens because the FNFE was thrown and caught *before the body of the `try` statement was executed*.

Basically, you can&#39;t use the logging system to log that you couldn&#39;t configure the logging system.  The best you can do is to write the error message directly to *standard error* and hope that it goes somewhere useful.

Note: replacing `new FileInputStream(&quot;src/main/resources/log.config&quot;)` with something that can actually find the file (or a resource) will cure the FNFE that triggered the NPE in this case.  But that&#39;s not the end of it.  What if (say) the resource is missing?  What it the file or resource is found, but it contains an garbled logging configuration.  **You will still get the NPE!**

Basically, the `LOGGER.log(Level.WARNING, &quot;Error &quot;, e);` statement is wrong.  It won&#39;t ever work as you intend.  If you get to that line and try to use `LOGGER`, an NPE is inevitable.

